text: Fantastic video! Just a quick observation, in China, everything is digitalized now. There are Chinese apps and miniprograms for everything! There are reviews available for virtually everything too (reliable and unreliable ones same as in Google). Unlike our Western countries, China has developed its own ecosystem of apps by displacing the American tech monopolies (nobody banned them, they refused to comply with the local laws and left for good). If you check the few countries that have their own alternatives to the major tech giants like META, Google, and Microsoft, they are all labeled as "the axis of evil" but the reality is that they just pushed for their own independence and refused to bow down to these American monopolies to build their own. You saw the facts about China in person now, I'm glad more people can see it by visiting this beautiful country. Cheers from Shanghai!

text:
I have met a young couple in Thailand recently. They were from US and flow to Singapore and they were traveling from Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand and then to Cambodia and Vietnam and before going back to US. 
We have happened to have a casual friendly conversation and I have asked them since they are so near to China, why not go to China just for a few days to see China. I told them China is very interesting. But I was surprised of what they told me. 
They said according to all their media reports in US and advice by their government and many other people. They were advice and told not to travel to China. Even their parents don't allow them to go to China. They were told China is not a safe country to travel. Very dirty, poor rundown infrastructures, poor transportation system, polluted, homeless people are everywhere waiting to rob tourists are common even in broad daylight. Chances of been detained for no reason by the Communist government is very high. Because China is an authoritarian state and all foreign visitors are monitored by thousands of cameras everywhere and every minute where foreign visitors go. Foreign visitors from western countries can be detained for months or even years for no reason. 
All these is what they know about China. The couple is like below 25 years of age and already so badly brainwashed by their government and controlled media. This is really sad.

text:
As an American, it's so easy for us to think of China as a bad place due to our own government's propoganda against them.
I'm from Seattle, Washington and visited Shanghai last year (2023)... and let me tell you, what an AMAZING experience it was!! The city was so clean, the infrastructure is efficient, the food is to die for, and most of all... the people are incredibly polite and friendly to foreigners! Well...maybe not the "older" people so much. It's not that they are outwardly or intentionally rude to you or anything like that... it just seems like  they'd rather just not interact with you? But the younger / middle-aged folks are amazingly inviting and friendly, and bexause Shanghai has such a strong Western-influence, I'd say that at least 80% of its citizens can speak English to some extent or another. I speak VERRRRY LITTLE Chinese and I had no problems at all interacting with ordinary people on the street, shop employees, and food vendors.
Anyway... if you're watching this video to learn about traveling to Shanghai, go for it!! My girfriend and I are already planning our next trip there for a 3-week vacation in 2025! So excited for this 👍👍

text:
I just came back from Shanghai. I have been to various parts of China. Shanghai cannot be equated with the rest of China though. Shanghai should be compared to Tokyo, Seoul or Singapore. It is ultra modern and affluent. Really a first rate city better than most cities in the Western world. Safe, clean, efficient and still affordable.

Nevertheless other "lesser" cities in China are pretty impressive too.  No matter what those China haters think or say, China has gotten many things right.

Not perfect. Some people are still not living up to the modernity of the place. Eg indiscriminately smoking and riding their electric bike on pedestrian ways. 

Despite that China has improved leaps and bounds. The high speed rail is efficient and basically works great despite a very reasonable fare. I think it is making losses but the China gov is supporting it

text: As an international student in London, after watching your video, I wanted to say that you are truly traveling in a very safe country. You don't need to worry about having your phone snatched or your wallet stolen—those things that can ruin a trip. China is a country that you need to experience firsthand, rather than believing in the so-called propaganda from the West. The area you’re in, Shanghai, is part of the East China region, which means it's in the eastern part of the country. This region has a preference for sweet flavors in its cuisine, which is why the soup dumplings (xiaolongbao) are sweet. In fact, China has a culinary history that spans thousands of years. If you love spicy food, I recommend visiting Chengdu or Chongqing. If you prefer salty flavors, the northern cities like Beijing or Shenyang would be great choices. If you enjoy seafood, you can visit coastal cities like Dalian, Xiamen, or Qingdao—these are all major cities in China. By the way, if you need help during your travels in China, the best approach is to ask university students you meet along the way. They often speak good English and can communicate well with you. Don’t be shy about asking questions—they will be more than happy to assist you!

text:
Living in China is indeed good, provided you're not Chinese.

Don't believe the viewpoints of travel channel YouTubers. These people are often naive and foolish, thinking China is great after wandering around a few big cities and believing that Western media is lying. Their open minds are like fortresses without walls.

Take this YouTuber as an example. He has 0.46 million subscribers. If you have such influence in China, you must provide your real name information to the government, and the police will periodically send people to check your browsing history, so you cannot express any dissatisfaction with the government.

If you are just coming to China for fun and leisure, you certainly won't encounter such problems. You don't realize that the apparent cleanliness and order are the results of indoctrination, that people are earning extremely low wages, and that they follow a culture of devotion and self-sacrifice.

I strongly warn you not to be deceived by the appearance that China presents and not to believe any Chinese person who says "foreigners are welcome to express their opinions freely." This friendliness is only towards foreigners. China is a society where people prey on each other.

text: Welcome, dear travelers from afar! China is a vast land with a rich history, diverse cultures, and breathtaking landscapes. Come explore the ancient cities like Beijing, Shanghai, and Xi'an, where you can witness the grandeur of the Forbidden City, the hustle and bustle of Pudong, and the Terracotta Warriors of the Qin Dynasty. Venture into the lush countryside, where rice paddies stretch as far as the eye can see, and the air is filled with the scent of jasmine tea. Taste the delicious cuisine, from spicy Sichuan dishes to the sweet dim sum of Hong Kong. Engage with the friendly locals, who are eager to share their stories and culture. Come discover the real China, a country that is both ancient and modern, traditional and innovative. You'll find that China is truly a land of wonders, waiting for you to uncover its secrets.

text: Vlog很不错！其实在中国旅游10天、短居1年或长居10年的感受是各不相同的，各个地区也差异巨大。在门户城市旅游10天你能品尝美食、感受中国现代化的城市发展；短居1年则能感受到低使用成本的基建、安全的环境、便捷的外卖、强大的线上购物和物流；长居10年或许能体会到中国的痛点，比如法治的不完善、劳工权益、食品药品安全等问题。虽然中国尚不完美，但坚韧不拔的中国人民必将把她建设得越来越好！这也是我爱这片土地的原因！最后，欢迎你再来中国游玩！

text: Very high quality video. Appreciate it as a Chinese🇨🇳. But I wanna correct one thing you mentioned by the end of the vlog about traveling here makes you feel disassociating with Internet Economy and having a life before the Internet. It is totally delusion or wrong perception, just cuz you don't know what's the replacing app of Google Map or other apps in China. Indeed, the online economy is the most advanced and dominating part in this country, 95percent of we citizens have to check the rating point of the restaurants, shops, hotels and hotspots we wanna go before we leaving home. However, it is quite normal for foreigners holding misunderstanding towards Chinese economy. all in all, thanks for advertising all stunning part of my country, really appreciate that! and as the local, my advice is all vlogs you filmed right now is a little bit superficial.. that will be perfect if you can study and absorb more economic and political  knowledge/ history of this ancient land, then the video gonna be more enlightening for audiences. love and peace .~ keep on moving on. respect

text:
Hi there! I just wanted to let you know that the breakfast you had at the beginning of your video is a popular snack from Shandong Province. 
In China, there are a few other popular map apps that you might find useful. 高德Gaode Maps and 百度Baidu Maps are both widely used and offer features similar to Google Maps.
If you're looking to order food delivery, there are also a few popular apps in China. 饿了么Eleme and 美团Meituan are two of the most popular options. They offer a wide variety of restaurants to choose from, and you can usually get your food delivered within 30 minutes .
Finally, if you're looking for recommendations on things to do or places to eat, you can check out 大众点评. It's a Chinese app that offers user reviews of restaurants, attractions, and other businesses.
I hope this information is helpful! Have a great time in China！

Those elders were playing Xian Qi. It is the Chinese version of Chess , and is very similar to chess
King is General -Same moves 
NO Queen, but instead two Counsels next to the General 
Two Bishops -Same but a little bit different moves
Two Knights = Horses 
Two Rooks = Two Carts-Same moves 
Pawns =Soldiers
And Chinese Chess has two Canons

text:
It’s not that China blocks them, but that Google, Facebook, Instagram and X refuse to obey Chinese laws, so they pull out of the Chinese market on their own.  It’s different than TikTok obeying American laws but still got banned.  Two different scenarios.  I am saying this as a Chinese American living in USA but with relatives still living in China.

That place is called Cheng Huang Miao 城隍廟 or the City God Temple area, with the Nine Turned Bridge (Zigzag Bridge) Jiu Qu Qiao 九曲橋 that leads into the Yu Garden.  

Chinese use their own national brands of apps, such as Baidu instead of Google, Baidu Map instead of Google or Apple Map, Bilibili and Youku instead of YouTube, Weibo and WeChat (Weixin) and Douyin (Chinese version of TikTok) instead of other social media’s.  China has their own Beidou GPS system.

https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/City_God_Temple_of_Shanghai

text: Fantastic video! Just a quick observation, in China, everything is digitalized now. There are Chinese apps and miniprograms for everything! There are reviews available for virtually everything too (reliable and unreliable ones same as in Google). Unlike our Western countries, China has developed its own ecosystem of apps by displacing the American tech monopolies (nobody banned them, they refused to comply with the local laws and left for good). If you check the few countries that have their own alternatives to the major tech giants like META, Google, and Microsoft, they are all labeled as "the axis of evil" but the reality is that they just pushed for their own independence and refused to bow down to these American monopolies to build their own. You saw the facts about China in person now, I'm glad more people can see it by visiting this beautiful country. Cheers from Shanghai!

text:
I have met a young couple in Thailand recently. They were from US and flow to Singapore and they were traveling from Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand and then to Cambodia and Vietnam and before going back to US. 
We have happened to have a casual friendly conversation and I have asked them since they are so near to China, why not go to China just for a few days to see China. I told them China is very interesting. But I was surprised of what they told me. 
They said according to all their media reports in US and advice by their government and many other people. They were advice and told not to travel to China. Even their parents don't allow them to go to China. They were told China is not a safe country to travel. Very dirty, poor rundown infrastructures, poor transportation system, polluted, homeless people are everywhere waiting to rob tourists are common even in broad daylight. Chances of been detained for no reason by the Communist government is very high. Because China is an authoritarian state and all foreign visitors are monitored by thousands of cameras everywhere and every minute where foreign visitors go. Foreign visitors from western countries can be detained for months or even years for no reason. 
All these is what they know about China. The couple is like below 25 years of age and already so badly brainwashed by their government and controlled media. This is really sad.
